    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-11-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-11-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="1036"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1036">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Conference files, lot 59 D 95, CF 134</note>
                <head>No. 1036<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum for the <gloss type="from">Executive Secretariat by
                            the Special Assistant</gloss> to the Secretary of State (<persName
                            corresp="#p_KJC1" type="to">Kitchen</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-11-27">November 27,
                            1952</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Secretary told me that Mr. <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName> talked
                    to him regarding Egypt on Tuesday afternoon. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_ESA1"
                        >Eden</persName> said that he had a number of reports indicating internal
                    difficulties which were making things difficult for <persName corresp="#p_NGM1"
                        >Naguib</persName> and his group. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_ESA1"
                        >Eden</persName> was of the opinion that <persName corresp="#p_NGM1"
                        >Naguib</persName> needed help. <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName>
                    said that his Government favored economic assistance as soon as possible in
                    order to stabilize the situation. The British could not provide economic
                    assistance, but they could provide some arms and military equipment. If the
                    United States had a choice between providing military equipment or economic
                    assistance, the British hoped that the United States would concentrate on the
                    latter. He remarked that the United States could leave the procurement of arms
                    from this country in commercial channels, thereby freeing United States
                    governmental assistance to concentrate in the economic field.</p>
                <p>The Secretary told Mr. <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName> that this
                    seemed a reasonable proposition to him and that he would tell the Department of
                    State to see what could be done and get on with the job as quickly as
                        possible.<note n="1" xml:id="d1036fn1">The following handwritten notation
                        appears on this memorandum: “Telephoned to Washington to <gloss
                            target="#t_SS1">S/S</gloss>–<persName corresp="#p_MFE1">Meloy</persName>
                        11/28/52, a.m., MA”.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KJC1">
                            <hi rend="strong">JCK</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
